---
import Card from '@asc-engineering/design-system/components/Card.astro';
import Stack from '@asc-engineering/design-system/components/Stack.astro';
import PageSection from '../layout/PageSection.astro';
---

<PageSection id="hobbies" title="Hobbies & Interests">
  <Stack direction="vertical" size="md">
    <Card variant="default" size="md">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">Typography</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
        I have a deep passion for Swiss typography — the design tradition that
        emerged from Basel and Zürich in the mid-twentieth century and reshaped
        how the world thinks about visual communication. Rooted in the <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Typographic_Style"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >International Typographic Style</a
        >, it champions mathematical grids, sans-serif typefaces (<a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helvetica"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Helvetica</a
        > by <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Max_Miedinger"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Max Miedinger</a
        >, <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Univers"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Univers</a
        > by <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrian_Frutiger"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Adrian Frutiger</a
        >, <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akzidenz-Grotesk"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Akzidenz-Grotesk</a
        >), and the principle that clarity is never an accident.
      </p>
      <p
        class="text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed pt-3"
      >
        What draws me to this discipline is the same instinct that drives good
        software architecture: reduce noise, expose structure, and let the
        content breathe. The grid is a constraint that liberates — much like a
        well-defined API contract or a rigorous type system. I collect printed
        specimens, study the work of <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josef_M%C3%BCller-Brockmann"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Josef Müller-Brockmann</a
        > and <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emil_Ruder"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Emil Ruder</a
        >, and apply these principles wherever I can — from slide decks to
        documentation to this site itself.
      </p>
    </Card>

    <Card variant="default" size="md">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">
        Philosophy of Mind
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
        The questions that animate philosophy of mind are, for me, the deepest
        ones: What is the relationship between thought and language? Can meaning
        be reduced to computation? Is the mind a kind of machine — and if so,
        what kind? My interest traces back to the analytic tradition, beginning
        with <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottlob_Frege"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Gottlob Frege</a
        >'s foundational distinction between sense and reference — the insight
        that meaning is not simply denotation, and that two expressions can pick
        out the same object while differing in how they present it. That
        seemingly technical point turns out to have enormous consequences for
        how we think about thought itself.
      </p>
      <p
        class="text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed pt-3"
      >
        <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ludwig_Wittgenstein"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Ludwig Wittgenstein</a
        > — both the early Wittgenstein of the <em>Tractatus</em> and the later Wittgenstein
        of the <em>Philosophical Investigations</em> — is a constant companion. The
        later work in particular, with its insistence that meaning is use and that
        private languages are incoherent, poses a direct challenge to any internalist
        picture of mind. <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W._V._O._Quine"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >W. V. O. Quine</a
        >'s radical holism — the indeterminacy of translation, the web-of-belief
        metaphor — deepened my appreciation of just how difficult it is to
        anchor meaning in anything stable.
      </p>
      <p
        class="text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed pt-3"
      >
        The thinker I keep returning to most is <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jerry_Fodor"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Jerry Fodor</a
        >. His <em>Language of Thought</em> hypothesis — that cognition operates over
        a structured system of mental representations with combinatorial syntax and
        semantics — feels to me like the most serious attempt to make the computational
        metaphor of mind genuinely precise.
        <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Modularity_of_Mind"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          ><em>The Modularity of Mind</em></a
        > changed how I think about software architecture: the idea that cognitive
        systems are decomposable into informationally encapsulated modules maps almost
        directly onto good interface design. Fodor's late pessimism about central
        systems — his honest admission that we have no good theory of how the modules
        integrate — is, paradoxically, what I find most intellectually bracing about
        his work.
      </p>
      <p
        class="text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed pt-3"
      >
        <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noam_Chomsky"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Noam Chomsky</a
        >'s argument for an innate universal grammar — and more broadly for a
        nativist, rationalist picture of the mind — sits in productive tension
        with the externalism of <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilary_Putnam"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Hilary Putnam</a
        >. Putnam's Twin Earth thought experiment — the claim that meanings
        "ain't in the head" — is one of the most elegant philosophical arguments
        I know, and it remains a live challenge for any purely internalist
        semantics. The debate between these two poles is, for me, still
        unresolved and still worth caring about.
      </p>
    </Card>

    <Card variant="default" size="md">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">Cinema</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
        I am drawn to films that treat the image as a primary language — where
        composition, light, and silence carry as much meaning as dialogue. The
        directors I return to most are <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wong_Kar-wai"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Wong Kar-wai</a
        > and <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wim_Wenders"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Wim Wenders</a
        > and <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stanley_Kubrick"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Stanley Kubrick</a
        > and
        <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Scorsese"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Martin Scorsese</a
        > and <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Ford_Coppola"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Francis Ford Coppola</a
        > — filmmakers who understand that cinema's deepest subject is the passage
        of time and the weight of longing.
      </p>
      <p
        class="text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed pt-3"
      >
        Wong Kar-wai's work — <a
          href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0118694/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          ><em>In the Mood for Love</em></a
        >, <a
          href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0109424/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          ><em>Chungking Express</em></a
        >, <a
          href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0212712/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          ><em>2046</em></a
        > — uses fractured chronology and saturated colour to make memory feel physical.
        Wim Wenders, in films like <a
          href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0087884/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          ><em>Paris, Texas</em></a
        > and <a
          href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0093587/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          ><em>Wings of Desire</em></a
        >, maps interior states onto landscapes with a patience few directors
        can sustain. What unites them is an aesthetic rigour that echoes, for
        me, the same values I find in Swiss typography: every frame is a
        considered act, nothing is accidental.
      </p>
      <p
        class="text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed pt-3"
      >
        I also have a soft spot for the films of the Coen Brothers, whose blend
        of dark humour and existential dread feels like a sibling to the
        absurdity I find in software development. <a
          href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0086250/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          ><em>Raising Arizona</em></a
        >, <a
          href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0116282/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          ><em>Fargo</em></a
        >, <a
          href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0103776/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          ><em>Big Lebowski</em></a
        >. <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woody_Allen"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          >Woody Allen</a
        >'s early work, with its neurotic charm and New York sensibility, also
        holds a special place in my heart. <a
          href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0075686/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          ><em>Annie Hall</em></a
        >, Sweet and Lowdown, and <a
          href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0083929/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
          ><em>Manhattan</em></a
        > are endlessly rewatchable.
      </p>
      <p
        class="text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed pt-3"
      >
        And now let's go bowling 🎳.
      </p>
    </Card>
  </Stack>
</PageSection>
